body: Yeah, let's bring up patching in today's triage meeting.
this one still repros on main. Will investigate for the fix

problem here is that in groupby scenarios, we clone the subquery and assign new alias to it. However TableMap is stored in form of Dictionary<ITableBase, string>, so the (cloning) visitor doesn't go through it and doesn't update table to the new alias (since it's not an expression). Later when we try to produce complex type columns (in the GenerateComplexPropertyShaperExpression) we use the old alias, and that results in bad sql. @roji

Thanks for the investigation @maumar, another bug of mine... :(

It should be pretty straightforward to have the cloning visitor update the table map - if memory serves, in the 8.0 codebase it already manipulates non-expressresions on EntityTypeProjectionBindingExpression. However, this is an area of the code that changed quite a lot in main, so backporting may not be as straightforward.

I'd suggest fixing in main for now and waiting to see how many people run into this before backporting...

issue.title: Fix to #33183 - Complex property causes "The multi-part identifier "xxx" could not be bound" after GroupBy + Select(x => x.First())

repository.name: efcore
repository.description: EF Core is a modern object-database mapper for .NET. It supports LINQ queries, change tracking, updates, and schema migrations.

issue.body:
Problem was that for group by we clone shaper expression and in case we cloned a table, we assign new aliases to all the columns associated with that table. However, we were not updating TableAlias values on StructuralTypeProjectionExpression. Later, when we try to generate columns for complex properties (in GenerateComplexPropertyShaperExpression) we were using incorrect alias (original one, rather than updated). Fix is to manually update TableMap when cloning StructuralTypeProjectionExpression

Fixes #33183
